        "last_activity_date": 1299260817,
        "creation_date": 1299257733,
        "answer_count": 2,
        "title": "Is there a function that strips HTTP response headers?",
        "body": "<p><strong>HttpResponse.getEntity().getContent()<\/strong> returns <em>everything<\/em>... including response headers, javascript code, response body (of course!) etc.<\/p>\n\n<p>Is there a function that cleans this up and provides <em>only the response body<\/em>? <\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 5196803,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "android",
            "html"
        ],
        "score": 0,
        "accepted_answer_id": 5196836,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 1519
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/vSVkO.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 320279,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 638471,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/638471/vbence",
                "reputation": 20391,
                "display_name": "vbence",
                "accept_rate": 83
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1299257961,
            "creation_date": 1299257961,
            "body": "<p>You have to read the data from the InputStream to a buffer. Search for this regex:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>\\r\\n\\r\\n(.*)\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This will give you the things after the header.<\/p>\n\n<p>Or you can replace it with an empty string, if you are searching for:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>^.*?\\r\\n\\r\\n\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 5196836,
            "question_id": 5196803
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/17f219cd389730e9fd42cc3dbfd776d3?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 319665,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 637545,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/637545/biddulph-r",
                "reputation": 5266,
                "display_name": "biddulph.r"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1299260817,
            "creation_date": 1299260817,
            "body": "<p>You can filter out patterns using Android with your own method. Pass in the String, and apply pattern filters to remove things you don't want.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public String filter(String searchString)\n    {\n        String content = searchString;\n        // Remove the new line characters.\n        Pattern newLineChar = Pattern.compile(\"\\n+\");\n        Matcher mLine = newLineChar.matcher(content);\n        while (mLine.find())\n            content = mLine.replaceAll(\"\");\n        // Return the clean content\n        return content;\n    }\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>You can get quite complicated with your patterns, and filter pretty much any expression you want. (You may need to use regular expressions etc). The example above replaces a new line (\\n) with 0 length string, to remove all of them from the string. You can build up patterns, or you can just iterate through again to remove something else.<\/p>\n\n<p>You will also need a couple of imports for this to work:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>import java.util.regex.Matcher;\nimport java.util.regex.Pattern;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 5197352,
            "question_id": 5196803
        }
    ],
